      <div xml:id="NA351-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu tōḻi arukutoṭuttatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante came close [to the matter].</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA351">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            iḷamai tīrntaṉa ḷivaḷeṉa vaḷamaṉai</l>
<l>            yaruṅkaṭip paṭuttaṉai yāyiṉuñ ciṟantivaḷ</l>
<l>            pacantaṉa ḷeṉpa tuṇarāy paṉṉā</l>
<l>            ḷevva neñcamoṭu teyvam pēṇi</l>
<l>            varuntal vāḻivēṇ ṭaṉṉai karuntāḷ</l>
<l>            vēṅkaiyaṅ kavaṭṭiṭaic cāntiṟ ceyta</l>
<l>            kaḷiṟṟuttup pañcāp puliyata ḷitaṇattuc</l>
<l>            ciṟutiṉai viyaṉpuṉaṅ kāppiṟ</l>
<l>            peṟukuvaṇ maṉṉōveṉ ṟōḻitaṉ ṉalaṉē</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent">Even if you have put [her] under heavy protection</l>
<l rend="indent2">in the wealthy house, saying</l>
<l rend="indent4">“she has come to the end of youth<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">iḷamai</term> here obviously refers to the period of childhood − sexual immaturity.</note>”,</l>
<l>you, not aware<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">uṇarāy</term> can also be read as an imperative: "be aware of".</note> of the fact that(?)<note place="foot">Actually we find in this position not the usual quotative particle <term xml:lang="ta">eṉa</term>, but a fully fledged verbal noun of the i.a. neuter singular. Is this just a sort of emphasis (to be rendered as above) or do we have to take it literally, namely as referring to the fact that someone (the confidante, the people of the village) are speaking of HER: “you are not aware of [them] saying ‘she has become very pale’”.</note> she has become very pale,</l>
<l rend="indent">many days, honouring the god with a troubled heart,</l>
<l>don’t suffer, live, please try(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">vēṇṭu</term>, the verbal root probably has to be read as an imperative in the function of an action-impelling particle.</note>, mother.</l>
<l rend="indent">If she guards the wide field of little millet</l>
<l rend="indent">from the platform with a tiger skin, without fear of the elephant</l>
<l rend="indent">bull’s vigour,<note place="foot">Here the sentence is ambiguous: either the girl need not be afraid of the elephant bull (coming to take the millet), since she is on a platform, or the platform is covered by the skin of a fearless tiger.</note></l>
<l rend="indent2">made of sandal wood<note place="foot">What is it supposed to mean that the <term xml:lang="ta">itaṇ</term> would be made of sandal wood?</note> on a branch of the black-trunked Vēṅkai,</l>
<l>won’t my friend get [back] her innocence?</l>
      </lg>
      </div>
